        <p>﻿# Setting Up an AI Companion as a Discord Bot Through Letta</p>
<p>A practical guide for building a Discord-based AI companion that uses a Letta agent as its memory-backed conversational brain.</p>
<p>This guide is written from the Ryuu K Discord bot setup, but the structure can be reused for any AI companion bot.</p>
<hr class="rule" />
<h2 id="1-what-you-are-building">1. What You Are Building</h2>
<p>You are building a Discord bot that:</p>
<ul>
<li>logs into Discord as a bot user</li>
<li>listens for commands, mentions, or DMs</li>
<li>sends selected prompts to a Letta agent</li>
<li>receives the Letta agent&#x27;s reply</li>
<li>posts replies back to Discord</li>
<li>can provide TL;DR summaries, vibe checks, catch-up reports, or casual conversation</li>
<li>can enforce privacy boundaries, cooldowns, and social safety rules</li>
</ul>
<p>The important distinction is:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Discord bot</strong> = the body/interface in Discord</li>
<li><strong>Letta agent</strong> = the companion&#x27;s memory, personality, and reasoning layer</li>
<li><strong>Bot code</strong> = the bridge between Discord and Letta</li>
</ul>
<p>In Ryuu&#x27;s case:</p>
<ul>
<li>Discord bot identity: <code>Ryuu K#5515</code></li>
<li>Letta agent identity: the persistent Ryuu/Felix companion agent</li>
<li>Bot folder: <code>Ryuu_RAG/discord-rag-bot/</code></li>
</ul>
<hr class="rule" />
<h2 id="2-high-level-architecture">2. High-Level Architecture</h2>
<p>A simple Letta-powered Discord companion looks like this:</p>
<div class="code-card"><span class="code-lang">text</span><pre><code>Discord user
   ↓
Discord message / command / mention
   ↓
Python Discord bot
   ↓
Prompt construction + guardrails
   ↓
Letta API
   ↓
Letta agent reply
   ↓
Python Discord bot
   ↓
Discord channel or DM response</code></pre></div>
<p>The bot should not just blindly forward every Discord message to Letta. It should decide:</p>
<ul>
<li>whether to respond at all</li>
<li>whether the user is allowed to use that feature</li>
<li>whether the response should be public or private</li>
<li>how much channel history to include</li>
<li>whether the request costs a Letta API call</li>
<li>whether privacy guardrails are needed</li>
<li>whether rate limits or cooldowns should apply</li>
</ul>
<hr class="rule" />
<h2 id="3-requirements">3. Requirements</h2>
<h3 id="3-1-accounts-and-services">3.1 Accounts and Services</h3>
<p>You need:</p>
<ol>
<li>A Discord account with access to the server where the bot will live.</li>
<li>A Discord Developer Portal application.</li>
<li>A Discord bot token.</li>
<li>A Letta account / server / API endpoint.</li>
<li>A Letta agent ID.</li>
<li>A machine that can keep the Python bot process running.</li>
</ol>
<p>For a personal setup, the machine can be a laptop or desktop. For a more reliable setup, use a VPS or always-on home server.</p>
<h3 id="3-2-local-software">3.2 Local Software</h3>
<p>Install:</p>
<ul>
<li>Python 3.10+</li>
<li><code>discord.py</code></li>
<li><code>python-dotenv</code></li>
<li><code>requests</code> or <code>httpx</code></li>
<li>optionally <code>aiohttp</code></li>
</ul>
<p>Example install:</p>
<div class="code-card"><span class="code-lang">powershell</span><pre><code>python -m pip install discord.py python-dotenv requests</code></pre></div>
<p>If you use a virtual environment:</p>
<div class="code-card"><span class="code-lang">powershell</span><pre><code>python -m venv .venv
.\.venv\Scripts\Activate.ps1
python -m pip install discord.py python-dotenv requests</code></pre></div>
<hr class="rule" />
<h2 id="4-create-the-discord-bot">4. Create the Discord Bot</h2>
<h3 id="4-1-create-an-application">4.1 Create an Application</h3>
<ol>
<li>Go to: https://discord.com/developers/applications</li>
<li>Click <strong>New Application</strong>.</li>
<li>Give it a name, e.g. <code>Ryuu K</code>.</li>
<li>Open the application.</li>
</ol>
<h3 id="4-2-create-the-bot-user">4.2 Create the Bot User</h3>
<ol>
<li>Go to <strong>Bot</strong> in the left sidebar.</li>
<li>Click <strong>Add Bot</strong> if needed.</li>
<li>Set the bot username and avatar.</li>
<li>Copy the bot token.</li>
<li>Store the token in <code>.env</code>, never directly in code.</li>
</ol>
<p>Example:</p>
<div class="code-card"><span class="code-lang">env</span><pre><code>DISCORD_TOKEN=your_discord_bot_token_here</code></pre></div>
<h3 id="4-3-enable-required-intents">4.3 Enable Required Intents</h3>
<p>In the Discord Developer Portal under <strong>Bot &gt; Privileged Gateway Intents</strong>, enable:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Message Content Intent</strong></li>
<li><strong>Server Members Intent</strong> if you need nicknames/member display names</li>
<li><strong>Presence Intent</strong> only if you actually need presence detection</li>
</ul>
<p>For a TL;DR bot, Message Content Intent is usually required.</p>
<h3 id="4-4-invite-the-bot-to-a-server">4.4 Invite the Bot to a Server</h3>
<p>Go to <strong>OAuth2 &gt; URL Generator</strong>.</p>
<p>Scopes:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>bot</code></li>
<li><code>applications.commands</code></li>
</ul>
<p>Common permissions:</p>
<ul>
<li>Read Messages/View Channels</li>
<li>Send Messages</li>
<li>Send Messages in Threads</li>
<li>Read Message History</li>
<li>Use Slash Commands</li>
<li>Embed Links, if needed</li>
<li>Attach Files, if needed</li>
</ul>
<p>Generate the URL, open it, and invite the bot to your server.</p>
<hr class="rule" />
<h2 id="5-create-or-choose-a-letta-agent">5. Create or Choose a Letta Agent</h2>
<p>Your Letta agent is the actual AI companion. It should contain the persona, memory, and behavioral rules.</p>
<p>You need:</p>
<div class="code-card"><span class="code-lang">env</span><pre><code>LETTA_BASE_URL=https://api.letta.com
LETTA_API_KEY=your_letta_key_here
LETTA_AGENT_ID=agent-id-here</code></pre></div>
<p>Depending on your Letta setup, the endpoint may differ. The bot should ideally support multiple endpoint formats because Letta APIs can vary across versions.</p>
<p>Common pattern:</p>
<div class="code-card"><span class="code-lang">text</span><pre><code>POST /v1/agents/{agent_id}/messages</code></pre></div>
<p>The bot sends a user message to the Letta agent and extracts the assistant reply.</p>
<hr class="rule" />
<h2 id="6-suggested-project-structure">6. Suggested Project Structure</h2>
<p>Example:</p>
<div class="code-card"><span class="code-lang">text</span><pre><code>discord-rag-bot/
  bot.py
  letta_client.py
  .env
  .env.example
  requirements.txt
  README.md
  ryuu_discord_bot.lock
  ryuu_discord_bot.out.log
  ryuu_discord_bot.err.log</code></pre></div>
<h3 id="bot-py"><code>bot.py</code></h3>
<p>Handles:</p>
<ul>
<li>Discord login</li>
<li>commands</li>
<li>message events</li>
<li>cooldowns</li>
<li>privacy guardrails</li>
<li>channel history fetches</li>
<li>DM/public reply routing</li>
<li>ambient comments/check-ins</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="letta-client-py"><code>letta_client.py</code></h3>
<p>Handles:</p>
<ul>
<li>Letta API authentication</li>
<li>sending messages to Letta</li>
<li>parsing Letta responses</li>
<li>friendly error handling</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="env"><code>.env</code></h3>
<p>Stores secrets and configuration.</p>
<p>Never commit <code>.env</code> to GitHub.</p>
<hr class="rule" />
<h2 id="7-example-env-configuration">7. Example <code>.env</code> Configuration</h2>
<div class="code-card"><span class="code-lang">env</span><pre><code># Discord
DISCORD_TOKEN=your_discord_bot_token
DISCORD_CLIENT_ID=your_discord_application_client_id
COMMAND_PREFIX=!

# Letta
LETTA_BASE_URL=https://api.letta.com
LETTA_API_KEY=your_letta_api_key
LETTA_AGENT_ID=agent-xxxxxxxx-xxxx-xxxx-xxxx-xxxxxxxxxxxx
LETTA_CONVERSATION_ID=

# Owner / trusted users
ALLOWED_USER_IDS=your_discord_user_id
ARTHUR_USER_ID=optional_special_user_id

# TL;DR behavior
DM_TLDR=true
MAX_TLDR_MESSAGES=200
PUBLIC_TLDR=true
PUBLIC_MENTIONS=true
